# JSDoc Conventions

Every exported function, class, and interface must have a JSDoc comment.
ESLint enforces this via `eslint-plugin-jsdoc`.

## First word rule

The first word of a JSDoc comment must be a verb in imperative mood.
Do not use a CamelCase identifier, a noun phrase, or a gerund as the
first word.

## Prohibited - common violations

```typescript
// WRONG - CamelCase identifier as first word
/** SubjectRepository handles database access for subjects. */

// WRONG - gerund (verb ending in -ing)
/** Getting all active subjects from the database. */

// WRONG - noun phrase
/** The result of querying subjects. */

// WRONG - past tense
/** Retrieved subjects filtered by status. */
```

## Required - imperative mood, plain English first word

```typescript
// CORRECT
/** Retrieve all active subjects ordered by name. */

/** Create a new subject and return the persisted DTO. */

/** Validate that the task title is non-empty and under 200 characters. */

/** Convert a database row to a SubjectDTO. */
```

## What gets a JSDoc comment

- All `export`ed functions
- All `export`ed classes and their public methods
- All `export`ed interfaces and their properties (if non-obvious)
- All IPC channel handlers

## What does not need a JSDoc comment

- Private class methods where the intent is clear from the name
- Test helper functions internal to a test file
- React component props interfaces with self-explanatory fields

## Parameters and return types

TypeScript type annotations are the source of truth for parameter types
and return types. Do not duplicate them in `@param` and `@returns` tags
unless the type alone does not convey the intent.

```typescript
// No @param/@returns needed - types are self-documenting
/** Create a new subject and return the persisted DTO. */
async function createSubject(input: CreateSubjectInput): Promise<SubjectDTO> { ... }

// @param needed - the intent of the parameter is not obvious from the type
/**
 * Execute the use case.
 * @param forceRefresh - when true, bypasses the in-memory cache
 */
async function execute(id: string, forceRefresh = false): Promise<SubjectDTO> { ... }
```

